Crimea and Sudetenland, same fight?
BRUSSELS – The Russian takeover of Crimea constitutes the most serious example of peacetime aggression that Europe has experienced since the annexation of the Sudetenland by Nazi Germany in 1938.
It is certainly today customary to minimize the importance of the "lessons of Munich" when referring to this episode in which Neville Chamberlain and Édouard Daladier conceded to Hitler's demands regarding Czechoslovakia in order to pacify the Führer.
Nevertheless, if the Western world were to close its eyes to the annexation of Crimea – the second case of invasion of a sovereign territory by Russian President Vladimir Putin, after the taking of the Georgian regions of Abkhazia and South Ossetia in 2008 – current democratic leaders might greatly regret their inaction.
Within Western capitals, reactions have so far been mixed.
The sanctions currently being considered – a expulsion from the G8, for example – might seem laughable if the threat to peace in Europe was not so serious.
Putin considers the collapse of the Soviet Union as the most serious catastrophe of modern times, the man striving ceaselessly to revive a fallen Russian empire.
If the West wants to be taken seriously, it will have to act with the same determination shown by Putin.
The many successes of the Russian president within the framework of his imperialist project have so far cost him almost nothing.
His initiative in favor of a Eurasian Economic Community has allowed Russia to bring together a number of resource-rich states, such as Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, and Turkmenistan.
Georgia was dismembered in 2008.
As for the Armenian government, Russian intimidations have pushed it to reject the association agreement proposed by the European Union.
And here comes the most precious geostrategic trophy of all – Ukraine – which could well fall into Putin's hands.
Without Ukraine, Russia "ceases to be an empire," as explained by the former American national security advisor Zbigniew Brzezinski; "on the contrary, with a bribed and then subordinated Ukraine, Russia automatically becomes an empire again." And since the vast majority of Ukrainians have no desire whatsoever to join Putin's empire, it is very likely that the country led by the Russian president will now become a highly militarized state, a sort of Soviet Union without a Communist Party.
It is essential that the international community's reaction be up to the level of the degree of adventurism displayed by Putin.
Cancellation of summits, proposals for trade agreements and other participations in as unproductive forums as the G8 will not be enough.
Only measures involving the imposition of tangible economic sanctions, capable of affecting Russian citizens – who, let us remember, continue to re-elect Putin to power – will allow us to hope to see the Kremlin abandon its expansionist course.
What sanctions could they be?
Firstly, Turkey could decide to close the Bosporus Strait to Russian transports, as it did after the Russo-Georgian War of 2008.
At that time, Turkey blocked access to the Black Sea in order to prevent the United States from intervening, although it is now clearly apparent that this was not the intention of the United States.
Today, Turkey could choose to close the Turkish straits not only to Russian warships, but also to all commercial ships heading to Russian ports in the Black Sea.
The impact on the Russian economy – as well as on Putin's military ambitions – would be considerable.
Turkey is authorized to close the Dardanelles under an amendment made in 1982 to the Montreux Convention of 1936.
Turkey could thus turn against Putin the very rationale he invoked to justify the takeover of Crimea – namely, that he would protect the Russian ethnic groups living there – by asserting itself as protecting its Turkish cousins of Tatar origin, who, given the mistreatment they have suffered at the hands of Russia, clearly wish to remain under Ukrainian rule.
This week, Turkish Foreign Minister Ahmet Davutoğlu ordered his plane to turn back in mid-air in order to head to Kiev to provide support to the new interim government.
Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, who, as Putin knows, is not exactly a softie, could thus follow suit by immediately closing the Turkish straits to Russian transports – until Putin recalls all his troops from Crimea so that they return to their bases, namely those of Sevastopol or Russia.
It would be good for Turkey to be able to count on the guarantee provided by Article 5 of the NATO treaty in the event that Russia attempts to intimidate it.
Secondly, American President Barack Obama could impose the same type of financial sanctions on Russia that he imposed on Iran regarding its nuclear program.
These sanctions indeed considerably crippled Iran's economy.
In the same way, refusing access to the American financial system for all banks dealing with Russian banks or companies would generate an unprecedented economic chaos in Russia since the fall of communism.
Russian citizens must understand that allowing Putin – whose rise to power is based on his promise to end the shortages of the early post-Soviet era – to continue his aggressive imperialist course could cost them dearly.
Thirdly, Obama could remind the Chinese of their role in Eurasian stability.
A true tragedy from Putin's perspective, the disintegration of the Soviet Union was the most extraordinary geostrategic windfall that one can imagine for China.
In an instant, this empire that had seized millions of hectares of Chinese territory over the centuries, and threatened the People's Republic with nuclear annihilation, simply vanished.
Since then, the independent states of Central Asia, and Ukraine itself, have become important trade partners for China.
The Russian invasion of Georgia seriously upset China, as was evident during the Shanghai Cooperation Organization summit held in the aftermath of the war (this regional grouping bringing together a number of former Soviet states with common borders with China and the motherland).
Russia attempted to get the SCO to recognize the independence of Abkhazia and South Ossetia.
The Organization nevertheless expressed its disagreement.
However, the Central Asian member countries – Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, and Uzbekistan – could never have opposed the Kremlin without the support of China.
It now falls to Chinese President Xi Jinping, however, to be less enigmatic in his response to Putin's audacity.
The true test of this Chinese claim to assert itself as a genuine and responsible protagonist within the international community will indeed take place very soon at the United Nations.
Will China support this manifest violation of international law committed by Putin, or will it stand in support of the territorial integrity of Ukraine?
Two other sanction avenues are also conceivable.
Each Russian leader could thus see their visas refused or canceled.
It would also be possible to freeze a number of assets, notably those that have been laundered by oligarchs close to Putin.
It is only when the pain becomes unbearable, and particularly for the elites, that this kind of struggle that Putin is conducting today could fail.
The price of inaction could well prove to be considerable.
Many countries, from Japan to Israel, rely on this promise of America to act firmly against any serious threat to peace.
Moreover, when Ukraine gave up its nuclear arsenal in 1994, it did so on the express condition that the United States (alongside the United Kingdom, France, and Russia) guarantee its territorial integrity.
If Crimea were to remain annexed, no one could blame Ukraine if it decided to renuclearize its defense (which it remains technologically capable of doing).
When Chamberlain returned from Munich, Winston Churchill addressed him with the famous phrase, "You had the choice between war and dishonor.
You have chosen dishonor, and you will have war." Obama and other Western leaders are today faced with a similar choice.
If they were to choose dishonor, we can be certain that the audacious Putin will eventually serve them a new war.
